text: I didn't know anything about this painting and Gustav Klimt until I bought, while visiting Prague, a plate that had this painting on it. Then I saw the documentary "The Rape of Europa" and learned about Maria Altman and her ten year struggle to successfully regain what was eventually proven to have been taken from her family. (The Austrian government had perpetuated a falsehood, that the painting had been donated by the family) I will definitely be going to see this movie, and when I go visit my sister in NY, I will go see the painting for myself at the Neue Galarie.

text: SHE JUST WANTED THE MONEY!!! From Wikipedia:Â  "The paintings left Austria in March 2006 and were on display at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art until June 30, 2006. Months after the Austrian government returned Altmann's family's belongings, she consigned the Klimt paintings to auction house Christie's, to be sold on behalf of her family. The painting Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I (1907) was sold to cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder for $135 million, at the time the highest sum ever paid for a painting. Since July 13, 2006, the painting has been on public display in the Neue Galerie in New York City, which was established by Lauder in 2001. The four additional works by Klimt were also exhibited at the Neue Gallerie for several weeks in 2006.[9] In November 2006, Adele Bloch-Bauer II (1912) was sold at auction at Christie's in New York fetching almost $88 million. In total, the four remaining paintings sold at auction for $192.7 million; coupled with the Lauder-bought painting the sum total was approximately $325 million. The proceeds were divided up among several heirs."
